<Project>

  <!--
    Microsoft.Testing.Platform.ServerClient.Source - consumer build customization
    =============================================================================
    This source-only package injects (as internal source) the MTP server-mode JSON-RPC client. The
    injected files are the exact protocol + serialization source the platform (server) compiles, so
    they expect the same compilation context the platform gives them. This targets file supplies that
    context to the consuming project.

    Imported for the DIRECT consumer only (every consumer compiles the source into its own assembly).
    It is a .targets (imported after the consumer's own PropertyGroups) so the values below always
    append, even if the consumer sets DefineConstants / NoWarn without $(DefineConstants) / $(NoWarn).
  -->
  <PropertyGroup>
    <!--
      Several linked platform files switch on IS_CORE_MTP (e.g. Helpers/ObjectPool.cs selects the
      Microsoft.Testing.Platform.Helpers namespace under IS_CORE_MTP, which Json.cs imports). The
      platform defines it while compiling; the injected source needs the same branch, so define it here.
      It is a platform-internal switch name that consuming code does not otherwise use.
    -->
    <DefineConstants>$(DefineConstants);IS_CORE_MTP</DefineConstants>

    <!--
      On net462 / netstandard2.0 the package injects down-level polyfills of compiler/BCL attributes
      (nullable annotations in System.Diagnostics.CodeAnalysis, Microsoft.CodeAnalysis.EmbeddedAttribute,
      etc.). A consumer that already provides the same types (for example through a referenced assembly)
      will get the benign CS0436 "the type in source conflicts with the imported type; using the one in
      source": the copies are marker attributes and behaviorally identical, so the source copy winning is
      safe. Suppress that specific benign collision so the injected source compiles under
      TreatWarningsAsErrors. (On .NET the polyfills compile to nothing, so no collision occurs there.)

      To instead DROP a specific polyfill family the consumer already ships, define the matching opt-out
      constant in your project rather than relying on this suppression, e.g.:
        <DefineConstants>$(DefineConstants);EXCLUDE_OS_POLYFILL;EXCLUDE_RANGE_INDEX_POLYFILL</DefineConstants>
    -->
    <NoWarn>$(NoWarn);CS0436</NoWarn>
  </PropertyGroup>

  <!--
    Note on .NET Framework (net462+) consumers:
    The injected source is authored for netstandard2.0, which includes some surface that is not in the
    in-box .NET Framework reference assemblies before 4.7.1 - notably
    System.Runtime.InteropServices.RuntimeInformation / OSPlatform. When a consumer REFERENCES a compiled
    netstandard2.0 DLL those types are satisfied by the netstandard facade + runtime shims; but a
    source-only package compiles its .cs directly into the consumer, and the net462 targeting pack has NO
    facade that forwards RuntimeInformation / OSPlatform (they simply do not exist on net462). Adding a
    <Reference Include="netstandard" /> does NOT help - a facade can only forward types the target
    framework actually has. So the two source sites that used those APIs are guarded with #if NETFRAMEWORK
    and fall back to net462-safe equivalents (Environment.OSVersion.Platform for the Windows check; constant
    false for the never-on-.NET-Framework OperatingSystem.IsWasi/IsAndroid/IsIOS/IsTvOS/IsBrowser checks).
    That keeps the package dependency-free and lets it compile clean on net462 with no extra references.
  -->

</Project>
